It was one of many rural sitcoms that populated CBS acreage during the 1960s (this series inspired---and shared characters with---the equally popular 'Green Acres'). Despite a revolving door of cast changes, the gentle, down-home comedy had a successful seven-year run.(n)

programme.title: Green Acres
programme.desc: A popular, broadly played hoot about a city couple enjoying life down on the farm. The show came on the heels of 'Petticoat Junction' and 'The Beverly Hillbillies,' making CBS the place to be for cornpone comedy in the 1960s. Regulars from 'Acres' and 'Junction' routinely crossed over---easy enough since both series were set in the town of Hooterville.(n)

programme.title: Mayberry R.F.D.
programme.desc: A hit spin-off from 'The Andy Griffith Show' about a gentleman farmer and widower who's elected to the Mayberry Town Council. Some of 'Griffith's' most endearing characters---Goober and Aunt Bee among them---moved over to this series, and that helped ensure its popularity, at least for a short time, as a gentle depiction of small-town life. In three years, however, despite still-strong ratings, CBS pulled the plug in a cutback of rural-oriented programming.(n)

programme.desc: James Cagney stepped into the shoes of legendary showman George M. Cohan and danced off with a Best Actor Oscar.
